		<credit project="CfPBoK@https://slebok.github.io/cfpbok/"/>
		<div class="right"><a href="index.html"><img src="../sle.png" alt="SLE 2010"></a><br><code>sle2010/paper17</code></div>
			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">SLE 2010</a> paper:</span><br><i>DSLTrans: A Turing Incomplete Transformation Language</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/BrunoBarroca.html">Bruno Barroca</a>, <a href="../profile/LucioLevi.html">Lucio Levi</a>, <a href="../profile/VascoAmaral.html">Vasco Amaral</a>, <a href="../profile/RobertoFélix.html">Roberto Félix</a>, <a href="../profile/VascoSousa.html">Vasco Sousa</a></h2>
<ul><li>DOI: <a href="https://doi.org/10.1007/978-3-642-19440-5_19">10.1007/978-3-642-19440-5_19</a></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t3b.html"><span class="tagM">T3B: Transformation Languages</span></a><ul><li> DSLTrans is explicitly a transformation language, designed to express model transformations.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t5d.html"><span class="tagL">T5D: Formal Methods</span></a><ul><li> Turing incompleteness is used to guarantee properties like termination and confluence, enabling verification by construction.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t4b.html"><span class="tagL">T4B: Horizontal Transformation</span></a><ul><li> Its constructs target systematic horizontal model mappings with traceable links and layered rules.
</li></ul></li></ul>
